They are not on Wednesday to reach an agreement on the future status of the province, during the last session of negotiations in Vienna.
In the end, the failure.
The Serbs and the Albanians of Kosovo have completed on Wednesday morning in Baden, in Austria, a sixth and ultimate meeting of discussions without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the Statute", has declared the European mediator Wolfgang ischinger, at a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was "concerned", its American counterpart, frank wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
"We do not envisage violence in the immediate future but we enter into a very difficult period," he added, raising that "obvious tensions exist."
At the end of the mediation on 10 December
The role of the troika, which is the European Union, the United States and Russia, will make a last Monday in Serbia and Kosovo.
The future of the province filled with 90% of albanophones could become clearer when ischinger, wisner and the Russian mediator Alexander botsane-khartchenko submit their report to the Security Council of the United Nations, here on 10 December.
The discussions in Baden, close to Vienna, constituted the sixth and last session of negotiations since the troika has been responsible for a new mediation by the UN, in August last year.
Americans and Europeans consider that their mediation will end on 10 December.
The Russians, who already have blocked at the Security Council the granting of independence in Kosovo, stress them on a continuation of the negotiations beyond this deadline.
"Russia was and remains engaged in favour of a negotiated solution, a compromise solution", has said botsane-khartchenko.
A unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of administration of Kosovo, the West believe that independence under the supervision of the EU is the only viable solution.
Pristina is said to be ready to declare it unilaterally if the Security Council does not cut in its favour.
Belgrade insists on an increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," has announced the President of the autonomous authority of Kosovo, Fatmir Sejdiu, in the hotel in Baden which have taken place since Monday these "negotiations of the last chance".
Hashim Thaci, former Commander of the rebellion and future Prime Minister of the province, part of its regrets.
But it has added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past that has led to the murders and deportations."
"domino effect"
The Serbian President Boris Tadic estimated for his part that a compromise was still possible, warning the Albanian majority in Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the independence of the province.
Belgrade said in particular to fear a "domino effect" in a region still weakened by the war of independence of the 1990s.
"for Serbia, he said, that does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision is allocated exclusively to the Security Council, where his Russian ally has a right of veto.
"the Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word"
"only a solution within the Security Council is acceptable for Serbia," said the Serbian Prime Minister, Vojislav Kostunica.
"these negotiations lasted two years ago.
They must end as they have started: in the Security Council.
Journalists, Fatmir sedjiu had replied that "the Parliament of Kosovo will have the last word on the Statute", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence from the albanophones do "," in cooperation with the West.
Bush extracts an agreement between Israelis and Palestinians
The President George Bush has announced, at the opening of the conference of international peace met by its care on Tuesday in annapolis, in Maryland, that the Israelis and the Palestinians were finally come to an agreement on a joint declaration.
He has clarified that the Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Olmert and the Palestinian President, Mahmoud Abbas had agreed to start immediately negotiations in order to find a definitive settlement of the dispute old 60 years between the two peoples.
In the presence of the two men, President Bush has promised that it would do everything to help to conclude a "Peace Treaty" before the end of the year 2008.
Meanwhile, the Palestinians have to dismantle the terrorist infrastructures "and Israel must put an end to its activities of colonization, Bush said, recalling the two parties to their obligations with regard to the" road map "for the peace that they have accepted in 2003.
The leader of the White House has pointed out that the negotiations between Israel and the Palestinian Authority chaired by Abbas would aim "to conclude a peace treaty solving all the unresolved questions, without exception, including the central questions".
This name covers three thorny problems at the heart of the dispute between Israelis and Palestinians: the future borders of Palestine, the status of Jerusalem and the fate of the Arab refugees driven out of their homes in what is now the State of Israel at the time of the conflict in 1948.
Speaking after the American President, Abbas has insisted that future negotiations are "global and deepened" and carry on all the aspects of a regulation, citing "Jerusalem, the refugees, the borders, the colonies, water, health, among others.
Going to turn to the platform, Olmert has involved the talks to come to be "direct and continuous" and "to make an effort to buckle in the current year".
Bush has set at the end of the year 2008 the deadline for implementation of the "vision of two States" Palestinian and Israeli that coexist.
The Saudi Arabia has revealed that it had obtained a commitment in this direction of Bush before deciding to take part in the Conference.
Arabia, whose participation in annapolis is a success for Washington, is at the origin of a plan, endorsed by all the Arab countries, which proposes the peace in Israel in return for its withdrawal from all the occupied Arab territories during the war of 1967, including Eastern Jerusalem.
Annapolis marks a crossroads in the history of the Middle East, especially because it attacks the roots of the conflict and to its central aspects ", considers the Prince Saud, in his interview in the daily Arabic-speaking in Saudi capital.
