The Bank of England takes note of the concerns in offering 10 billion pounds on five weeks
The Bank of England was said on Thursday anxious to reduce the actual return of anxiety about the conditions of credit, and announced an offer of ten billion pounds in the basic rate of 5.75% over five weeks, an offer of an unusual length.
"to relieve the concerns that the conditions of the financial market will be particularly tight at the end of the year, and to give to the banks greater certainty in the way in which they will organize their positions of liquidity over this period, the Bank has the intention to give a large proportion of its provision of reserves envisaged for the period of service beginning on 6 December in the form of an operation open market to five weeks", in a press release.
The Bank specifies that 10 billion pounds (14 billion euro) will thus be put on the market on 6 December at 12 H 15 GMT, at the base rate and until 10 January.
This is the first time it seems that the boe puts on the market liquidity to five weeks in an operation of open market.
These are normally in a week.
The boe add "in its statement that it is ready to take other measures to maintain the rate of loans" interbank every day in line with its basic rate.
The rate in the day to day was on Wednesday 5,829%.
The rate in three months was established to 6.6%, a higher for the 18 September.
Since the beginning of the financial crisis in the summer, are put on the market by the Bank of England was matched to a rate of important penalty which had dissuaded the banks have recourse.
According to some rumours, supported by the evolution of the course of the book in relation to the euro, a lot has preferred to subscribe to the are put on the market by the European Central Bank, in more favourable rates and with a surer discretion.
