The new business of gas from Russia and the Ukraine throws the alarm.
A dispute on the price of gas ferments between Ukraine and Russia, for example, the risks of repercussions on fuel exports to Europe.
The majority of the Russian gas exports to the European Union (E.U.) are by gas pipelines, and every canal is overseen.
Kiev has announced that if Russia increases the cost of fuel, it will increase the taxes of transit to Russia.
Last year, a dispute between the two, had caused a reduction of supplies to the countries of the E.U.
The last argument between Kiev and Moscow happens after the Ukrainian Government and Gazprom company of monopoly of ownership of Russia is supplying gas, have tried in vain to find an agreement on the cost of Russian gas provided to Ukraine for the year 2008.
Gazprom has declared that it would increase as planned, its prices to Ukraine, given that it has agreed to pay for 2008, up to 50% more for the supply of gas coming from Turkmenistan.
The analysts have declared that it would include for Ukraine, an increase of 40% of the costs of imports originating from Gazprom.
"It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the conversations, saying that we are a country through which the majority of gas, has announced the Ukrainian Minister for the economy, Anatoly kinkh to Reuters news agency.
"the fluctuations of the costs of the gas would undoubtedly linked to our discussions about the taxes of transit (to Western Europe via Ukraine")
The last great dispute between Moscow and Kiev has caused in January 2006, the interruption of supplies of Gazprom intended to Ukraine.
This has led to the fall of exports to Western Europe, increasing the prices by consequence.
The Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the supply of the European Union.
Russia has the biggest supplies of gas, even if the majority of them are still being developed.
In consequence, Gazprom completes its own supplies with gas coming Turkmenistan and other countries of the former Soviet Union in Central Asia.
