The Scottish Ministry of Health must improve the controls to be carried out on its extra-Community employees to check whether they have criminal precedents, has declared the Committee of control.
The warning of the general, Robert Black, has arisen after a foreign doctor working in Scotland, was involved in the attack at the airport of Glasgow of June.
Mr black in addition, expressed its concern about the fact that the Scottish Ministry of Health has no precise data on the number of people overseas that it uses.
His report has really highlighted other decisive controls, correctly carried out on a sample of employees of five health authorities.
The general has made controls on the Community extra personnel following the attack on the airport in Glasgow.
