The British bankers plead guilty to the Enron case.
The three British bankers who had to go to manifest their roles in relation to a fraud committed by the previous financial director of Enron, Mr Andrew fastow, have changed their declaration, pleading guilty on Wednesday.
David bermingham, Giles darby and Gary mulgrew were initially declared innocent of seven charges for presumed collusive fraud in 2000, made by fastow in a secret financial fraud in order to grow rich in spite of their employees.
They should be presented to the Court in January.
But during a hearing presided over by the American judge Ewing werlein jr, they are all found guilty of having made a fraud.
The three former frameworks of Greenwich natwest, a subsidiary of the group plc of the Royal bank of Scotland, became famous everywhere in the United Kingdom because of the extradition procedures which have lasted two years ago.
In the United States, their case is still an outstanding question for this inquiry launched following the collapse of Enron in 2001.
The charges that were brought in 2002, have made clear to fastow that it was the subject of the investigation of the government in the collapse of Enron.
The charges against the bankers, called the "three of natwest" claim to have come in Houston in 2000, to organize a fraudulent scenario with fastow and his former right-hand man, Michael kopper.
Natwest Greenwich has invested in a subsidiary of a partner of Enron controlled by fastow, which was the director of many fraudulent, who has helped it to the procedures of bankruptcy.
At the beginning of 2002, the Bank had considered its interest for the subsidiary as any, but in fact the three British men already its value.
A company controlled by kopper bought the interest of the Bank of the subsidiary to £1 million.
The bankers paid $250,000 to kopper as interest in this society.
According to the accused, fastow would have announced to Enron that society of energy was willing to pay $20 million to Greenwich natwest for its actions in the subsidiary.
But in truth these $20 million went into the pockets of the British bankers, fastow and others again.
According to the charges, the bankers had obtained $7.3 while fastow, kopper and others would have gained $12.3 million.
In January 2004, fastow pleaded guilty for its active role in both conspiracies in the collapse of Enron.
The British trio was arrested after three months.
Fastow has suffered a six years imprisonment in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is imprisoned for three years and a month in a prison in texarkana.
The three British have been released following the payment of a guarantee of $each, which oblige them to live in the United States during the process.
Enron, before seventh largest national society, in bankruptcy in December 2001 after years of accounting, could no longer hide his billion debt or even to propose its speculations can be profitable.
The collapse has caused thousands of redundancies, more than $60 billion of loss of value in the market, and more than $2 billion loss for the pension schemes.
The founder of Enron, Kenneth lay and the former President general Jeffrey skilling have been condemned last year, for their involvement in the collapse of the company.
Skilling has been sentenced to more than 24 years in prison.
The charges against lay for conspiracy, fraud and other offences have been empty because of his death due to a heart attack last year.
